[[Image:Lacus Excellentiae 4148 h2 h3.jpg|thumb|right|240px|[[Lunar Orbiter 4]] image showing approximately the same extent as the Clementine image above.]]
'''Lacus Excellentiae''' ([[Latin language|Latin]] for "Lake of Excellence") is a relatively small, irregular [[lunar mare]] in the southern latitudes of the [[Moon]], amidst the rugged terrain to the south of the larger [[Mare Humorum]]. The most prominent feature within the diameter of this basin is the small crater [[Clausius (crater)|Clausius]].

The [[selenographic coordinates]] of this feature are {{coord|35.4|S|44.0|W|globe:Moon}} and it lies within a diameter of 184&nbsp;km. The name of this lunar lake is a relatively recent addition to lunar nomenclature, being officially approved in 1976 by the [[International Astronomical Union|IAU General Assembly]].

The ''Lacus Excellentiae'' was the impact site of the [[SMART-1]] lunar orbiter. This probe impacted the lunar surface on September 3, 2006 and was observed by [[astronomer]]s to determine the properties of the ejected materials.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/5309656.stm | work=BBC News | title=Probe crashes into Moon's surface | date=2006-09-03 | accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref>

